18 Comments

Lactose anhydrous is one of the materials that have been selected for

harmonization by the Pharmacopeial Discussion Group. For further

information see the General Information Chapter <1196> in the

{{ drug.molecular_formula }}–NF27, the General Chapter 5.8 in PhEur 6.5, along with the

‘State of Work’ document on the PhEur {{ drug.molecular_formula }} website, and also

the General Information Chapter 8 in the JP XV.

Lactose anhydrous has been used experimentally in hydrophilic

matrix {{ drug.dosage_form }} formulations(8) and evaluated for dry powder

{{ drug.route_of_administration }} applications.(9,10) Partial hydration of anhydrous lactose

increases the specific surface area and reduces the flow properties of

powders but has no effect on compactibility.(11) A specification for

lactose is included in the {{ manufacturer.name }} Codex ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}(12)); see

Lactose, Monohydrate.

The {{ drug.molecular_formula }} number for lactose anhydrous is 200-559-2. The

PubChem Compound ID ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) for lactose anhydrous includes

6134 and 84571.
